                    <li>Research shows that lonely or isolated seniors are more likely to decline and die faster. One study found that older adults who reported feeling lonely had a 59% higher risk of mental and physical decline along with a 45% increase in their risk of death.</li>
                    <li>Seniors who live alone experience conditions such as chronic lung disease, arthritis, impaired mobility, and depression at higher rates than those with strong social support.</li>
